     <h2><font color="#000080"><!-- 2004-09-02 -->
	 
	 Weight Loss and the Cravings
	 </font>
     </h2>
    

	<p>
    <div style="clear:both;"></div><p><cite cite="http://headrush.typepad.com/creating_passionate_users/2006/05/the_strangest_e.html"><a href="http://headrush.typepad.com/creating_passionate_users/2006/05/the_strangest_e.html">Creating Passionate Users: The strangest, easiest way to lose weight</a></cite>.&nbsp; Kathy Sierra posted a remarkable experience on&nbsp;changing her physical-weight &ldquo;set point&rdquo; using&nbsp;Seth Robert&rsquo;s&nbsp;<em><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0399153640/">Shangri-La Diet: The No Hunger Eat Anything Weight-Loss Plan</a></em>.&nbsp; Based on Kathy&rsquo;s account and on observations made on the <a href="http://www.freakonomics.com/blog/2006/04/20/the-shangri-la-diet-between-hard-covers/">Freakonomics blog</a>, I have ordered the book.&nbsp; To&nbsp;achieve the&nbsp;no-shipping level, I&nbsp;had Amazon&nbsp;toss in <em><a href="http://www.freakonomics.com/thebook.php">Freakonomics</a></em>, a book I&rsquo;ve not yet read.</p><p align="center">{tags: <a href="http://technorati.com/tag/diet" rel="tag">diet</a> <a href="http://technorati.com/tag/exercise" rel="tag">exercise</a> <a href="http://technorati.com/tag/health" rel="tag">health</a> <a href="http://technorati.com/tag/food+craving" rel="tag">food craving</a> <a href="http://technorati.com/tag/Freakonomics" rel="tag">Freakonomics</a> <a href="http://technorati.com/tag/Shangri-La+Diet" rel="tag">Shangri-La Diet</a> <a href="http://technorati.com/tag/Kathy+Sierra" rel="tag">Kathy Sierra</a> <a href="http://technorati.com/tag/orcmid" rel="tag">orcmid</a>}</p><p>In Winter 2004&ndash;2005 I successfully brought my weight range from a high of 168 to a comfortable-for-me 155.&nbsp; Along with the exercise and diet regimen, I also brought my cholesterol levels to the best they&rsquo;ve ever been in the 20+ years that&nbsp;they&rsquo;ve &nbsp;been monitored and medicated.&nbsp; I relaxed out of that, and lately my weight is stuck around 160 and is not budging.&nbsp; </p><p>I have become careless about exercise, so I&rsquo;m putting daily exercise practices back in.&nbsp; I am working with an e-mail &ldquo;vitality buddy&rdquo; and reporting my weight, exercise, and other actions I&rsquo;m taking every day.&nbsp; This seems to have stabilized the creeping weight-gain, and it is extremely valuable in having me perform in this area.&nbsp; But I have pretty constant cravings and I respond&nbsp;by&nbsp;wolfing down&nbsp;snack foods.&nbsp; There are baby carrots in the refrigerator, and I must put that in.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s not where I look when I want a quick snack fix.&nbsp; I will make snacking on carrots, fruits and other vegetables an addition to what I account for with my vitality buddy and I&rsquo;ll put that into practice right now.</p><p>Meanwhile, I am looking forward to the book.&nbsp; I will also getting a cholesterol check-point in a month or&nbsp;two and it will be interesting to see if I have reclaimed any or all of my prior victory.&nbsp; I know that exercise was a big factor, and it was the only way I&rsquo;ve ever managed to raise my HDLs into the desired range.</p><p>My vitality buddy has been cutting back on caffeine, and I know Jeff Sandquist stopped drinking caffeine when he managed the <a href="http://www.jeffsandquist.com/PermaLink,guid,6af7870b-49f8-4a14-8257-2fcdfa2b04f5.aspx">weight reduction</a> that inspired my previous victory.&nbsp; I started doing the same, and I&rsquo;ve managed to reduce my intake to 1&ndash;2 cups of lip-smacking French Roast drip every two days.&nbsp; I learned something that I should have known.&nbsp; Caffeine works for me in managing my regular occurrences of sinus inflammation.&nbsp; So, in addition to becoming more lethargic than I was willing to continue, I found that caffeine was the best treatment when low-level allergy/sinus symptoms kick-in.&nbsp;&nbsp; That&rsquo;s my story.&nbsp; I don&rsquo;t think it is caffeine withdrawal.&nbsp; </p><p>Unfortunately, while in Mountain View on May 1&ndash;3 I became great buddies with the barista at the IIW2006 workshop and now must go into recovery.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s working, although I find that I have begun to crave coffee too.&nbsp; I also see, in reviewing my previous experience, that I no longer measure calories and that I lost my original coach&rsquo;s attention after that success.&nbsp;&nbsp; </p><p>At the bottom of all of this, I must embrace this effort as a journey and not as an end-point.&nbsp; I will never not be managing my weight, exercise, and overall health and vitality.&nbsp; Now it is time to click post and get on the rowing machine.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><div style="clear:both; padding-bottom: 0.25em;"></div>
    </p>
